{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502424"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:43:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:43:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1859"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1859","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1859"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.44,0.35,0.12,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1859"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90306"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1859","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1859"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1859"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74560"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"3467"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"296"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30969"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90306","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90306"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 43-year-old man is hospitalised with an episode of acute diverticulitis. He is usually in good health and has never had this problem before. He has localised left iliac tenderness, with evidence of diverticulae, thickening of the sigmoid colon and pericolic stranding seen on CT scanning. He is treated with antibiotics and bowel rest.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFive days after admission he is continuing to spike fevers and has persistent left iliac fossa pain and tenderness. A repeat CT scan shows a 5 cm pericolic abscess at the level of the pelvic brim.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Continue current management plan","Percutaneous drainage","Laparoscopy, lavage and drainage","Laparotomy, lavage and drainage","Laparotomy and sigmoid colectomy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has complicated diverticulitis with a Hinchey Stage II perforation. In other words, the perforation has extended outside the mesentery - and this has developed despite antibiotics and gut rest. Some form of intervention is now required and the least invasive will be \u003Cstrong\u003ECT-guided drainage\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst this perforation is contained (abscess formation), any larger collection or one situated such that CT-guided percutaneous was not feasible, would necessitate some form of surgical intervention. The least invasive would be a laparoscopic approach. Free perforation and evidence of suppurative peritonitis might need an open approach and at stage a decision might be made as to whether lavage and drainage would be satisfactory or if a resection of the disease section of bowel would be more practical.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Small intra-abdominal abscesses can usually be drained percutaneously."],"references":["Tochigi T, Kosugi C, Shuto K, et al. Management of complicated diverticulitis of the colon. Ann Gastroenterol Surg 2018; 2:22-27."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74560"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1859"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74560","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74560"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-13T17:09:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-13T1